<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="lesson3_5" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Simplification and Two-Qubit States</title>

  <p> With all of the tools in our toolkit, we can now finish off our understanding of dealing with
    superposition states and two-qubit states. </p>

  <section xml:id="sec-simplify-superposition-visual">
    <title>Simplification Rules for Visualized States</title>
    <p> Just like in algebra, complex quantum states can be simplified. Here are the rules to
      follow: <ul>
        <li>Negative signs outside a set of outcomes in a superposition can be <em>distributed</em>
      by applying the negative sign to each outcome within the superposition.</li>
        <li>Negative and positive versions of the same state in different possibilities cancel out.</li>
        <li>If all possible outcomes in a superposition state are identical, this is equivalent to
      that outcome without superposition.</li>
        <li>Since the number of balls corresponds to the probability of the outcome, if there is a
      common factor between the number of each outcome, you can reduce the number of balls as long
      as the <em>ratio</em> stays the same.</li>
        <li>The overall state can be multiplied by a negative sign without changing the state (we
      will
          learn more about this in the future).</li>
      </ul>
    </p>

    <sidebyside widths="75% 20%" valign="top">
      <p>
        The best way to see the effect of these rules is with an example. Suppose you have a
        one-qubit system and the result of applying a series of gates is the picture to the right;
        we can apply the rules above to simplify it:
      </p>

      <image source="L3.4-Simplify.png" width="10%" />
    </sidebyside>

    <p>
      Here's a step-by-step walkthrough of applying each rule on this state:</p>

    <image source="L3.4-SimplificationRules.png" width="90%" />

