  <section xml:id="sec-two-qubit-visual">
    <title>Visualizing Two-Qubit States</title>

    <p> At this point, it is important to introduce the visual representation for <em>two-qubit</em>
      states. As we have seen, a horizontal line divides between two different possible outcomes. To
      represent multiple qubits, we show two qubits (circles) without a horizontal line between
      them. The first qubit is the one on top, and the second is the one on the bottom. </p>

    <sidebyside widths="20% 20%" valign="top">
      <image source="Visual_Onebit_50_positive.png" width="20%" />
      <image source="L3-4-twoqubitvisual.png" width="20%" />
    </sidebyside>

    <!-- <image source="VisualRep_one_vs_two_qubits_OLD.png" width="40%" /> -->
    <!-- <image source="VisualRep_one_vs_two_qubits.png" width="50%" /> -->

    <!--
    <sidebyside widths="35% 15% 15% 35%" valign="top">
      <p> </p>

      <image source="Visual_Onebit_50_positive.png" width="10%" />
      <image source="L3-4-twoqubitvisual.png" width="10%" />
      <p> </p>
    </sidebyside>
    -->

    <p> In the images above, the left side is a single qubit in 50/50 superposition. The right side
      is two different qubits, one <m>\ket{0}</m> and the other <m>\ket{1}</m>.</p>

    <sidebyside widths="80% 10%" valign="middle">
      <p>
        We can combine these rules for
        visual representation for a two-qubit state in superposition. Here's an example:</p>
      <image source="L3.4-TwoQubitSuperposition.png" width="20%" />

    </sidebyside>

    <p>Some important notes about the state above: <ul>
        <li>We see that there are four possible outcomes of measuring this 2-qubit quantum state,
      divided by horizontal lines: <m>\ket{00}</m> , <m>\ket{01}</m>, <m>\ket{10}</m>, and <m>\ket{11}</m>. This is the standard
      convention for the order in which to show each outcome.</li>
        <li>The <m>\ket{01}</m> and <m>\ket{11}</m> states have <em>negative phase</em>. While this phase does not
      have any effect when we measure this state, this phase can have an effect based on gates
      applied to this state.</li>

      </ul></p>

    <p>We can combine our rules for simplifying superposition states with representing two-qubit
      states:</p>

    <exercise label="Visual-Rep-Simplification-2Qubit">
      <title>Simplifying 2-Qubit Visual Representation</title>
      <idx>simplifying 2-qubit visual representation</idx>
      <statement>
        <sidebyside widths="60% 10%">
          <p>What are all of the possible outcomes of measuring the following state?</p>
          <image source="L3-5-Simplify-2Q.png" width="10%" />
        </sidebyside>
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="no" multiple-correct="yes">
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p><m>\ket{00}</m> or ⚪⚪</p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p><m>\ket{01}</m> or ⚪⚫</p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <p><m>\ket{10}</m> or ⚫⚪</p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p><m>\ket{11}</m> or ⚫⚫</p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
      </choices>
      <hint>
        <p>
          Think about how to combine superposition states that are in superposition with each other.
        </p>
        <p>Be careful about distinguishing between superposition (where the balls are separated by a
          horizontal line) and different qubits (where balls are <em>not</em> separated by a
          horizontal line).</p>
        <p>Remember to read qubits top to bottom.</p>
      </hint>
    </exercise>
  </section>
</section>
